-- Credence Bounds as Invariants (CredTT-Native #2)
--
-- NEW: Prove lower bounds on c(A), upper bounds on c(neg A)
-- Maintain credence bounds as loop invariants
--
-- Example: Throughout computation, maintain c >= 0.9

-- Classical: invariants are boolean (holds or doesn't)
-- CredTT: invariants have CREDENCE (how strongly they hold)

-- LOWER BOUND: c(A) >= bound
-- "We're at least this confident in A"

postulate hypothesis : H @ c

-- Prove: c >= 0.9 (high confidence)
-- This is a meta-assertion about credence

-- UPPER BOUND: c(neg A) <= bound
-- "Negation has at most this credence"

-- If c(A) >= 0.9, then c(neg A) <= 0.1
-- Because c(neg A) = 1 - c(A)

-- INVARIANT MAINTENANCE:
-- In a loop, track how credence evolves

-- Iteration 0: c_0 = 1
-- Iteration 1: c_1 = c_0 * step_credence
-- Iteration n: c_n = step_credence^n

-- If step_credence = 0.99:
-- c_100 = 0.99^100 = 0.366
-- Credence degrades over iterations!

-- To maintain c >= 0.9 invariant:
-- Need step_credence >= 0.9^(1/n)
-- For 100 iterations: step >= 0.9^0.01 = 0.9989

-- This is WHY CredTT matters for verification:
-- It tracks credence degradation through loops
-- Classical verification ignores this

-- DUAL BOUNDS:
-- Prove both c(A) >= l and c(A) <= u
-- "Credence is in interval [l, u]"

-- If l = 0.4 and u = 0.6, we know:
-- A is probably true (> 0.5 midpoint)
-- But not definitely (< 1)
-- And not definitely false (> 0)

-- This is the INTERIOR region
-- CredTT can reason about it; classical logic cannot

-- Practical application:
-- Machine learning confidence scores
-- Statistical hypothesis testing
-- Bayesian inference bounds
